  "target_response": {
    "text": "It's starting to, but hold it loosely. In 9 tagged late-screen nights versus 38 comparison days, you slept about 21 minutes less on average — and with only 9 tagged nights that's a low-confidence pattern with obvious confounds, since late screens usually arrive with later bedtimes, later meals, and more stimulation generally. The screen may be the marker rather than the mechanism. This week leans the same way — last night you slept 419 minutes, about 22 minutes under your 7-day average of 441 minutes, and your HRV is 58 ms, just under your 7-day average HRV of 60 ms. Cheapest test: pick three nights this week, park the phone an hour before bed, and tag them. Ten more tagged nights either firms this up or clears the screens' name.",
